        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>limestone by composition: aggregate type [300011287], limestone by composition [300137624], limestone [300011286], carbonate rock [300011283], sedimentary rock by composition [300011274], sedimentary rock [300011273], rock (inorganic material) [300011692], inorganic material [300010360], materials by composition [300212963], materials (substances) [300010358], Materials (hierarchy name) [300010357], Materials Facet [300264091]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Variously defined limestones, occurring in Egypt and the Peloponnesus and extensively used as building materials by the ancient Greeks; apparently included several materials, such as tufa, travertine, fossiliferous limestone, and onyx marble.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000035491/Mitchell, Dictionary of Rocks (1985)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Calizas de diferente definición presentes en Egipto y en el Peloponeso y fueron utilizadas ampliamente como materiales de construcción por los antiguos Griegos. Aparentemente, incluían diversos materiales tales como tufa, travertino, caliza fosilífera y mármol de ónice.
</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Verschillend omschreven kalksteensoorten die voorkomen in Egypte en de Peloponnesus en op grote schaal werden gebruikt als bouwmateriaal door de oude Grieken. Blijkbaar werden er verschillende materialen onder verstaan zoals tuf, travertijn, fossielhoudende kalksteen en onyxmarmer.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指稱多種石灰岩，產於埃及和伯羅奔尼撒半島（Peloponnesus），為古希臘人當作建材大量使用。「波羅斯石」一詞可指多種材料，包括軟質石灰華、石灰華、化石石灰岩和縞瑪瑙大理石。 </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
